{
  "slug": "the-eddie-murphy-hall-of-fame-plus-mads-mikkelsen",
  "title": "The Eddie Murphy Hall of Fame. Plus: Mads Mikkelsen!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessy",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2021-03-05",
  "runtimeMin": 101,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda build a ten-film Eddie Murphy Hall of Fame with Van Lathan, then Thomas Vinterberg and Mads Mikkelsen talk through 'Another Round.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Coming 2 America, briefly",
      "note": "the sequel, thirty-plus years later",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Coming 2 America",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "A fine, familiar nostalgia lap that leans on old jokes rather than new ones. Wesley Snipes is the best part; the original is the one worth revisiting."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "So close: the final four maybes",
      "note": "what didn't make the ten",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Golden Child",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "Van's childhood favorite, even top five for him personally, but the others weren't sold."
        },
        {
          "title": "Beverly Hills Cop II",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Van's own movie-going awakening, but a sequel to a stronger original."
        },
        {
          "title": "Harlem Nights",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Eddie's directorial debut, a thank-you to Pryor and Redd Foxx, more meaningful to Van than to the other two."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bowfinger",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "A solid reputation and a favorite scene or two, but no room left."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Eddie Murphy Hall of Fame",
      "note": "with Van Lathan of Higher Learning",
      "honoree": "Eddie Murphy",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "48 Hrs.",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "A 22-year-old Eddie holds his own opposite Nick Nolte in a genuinely violent, adult buddy-cop movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Trading Places",
          "year": 1983,
          "note": "The panel's pick for his funniest performance, from before mega-fame, when he barely seems to know how funny he is."
        },
        {
          "title": "Beverly Hills Cop",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "The one that made him a movie star; Van knew the theme song before he'd seen the film."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eddie Murphy Raw",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "The highest-grossing stand-up film ever made. Dated in spots, but still an all-timer performance."
        },
        {
          "title": "Coming to America",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "The unanimous, instant yes. Eddie's said it's still the rare all-Black-cast studio film that's done well everywhere in the world."
        },
        {
          "title": "Boomerang",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "Poorly received and, per Amanda, weirdly racist coverage at the time. Now one of his most rewatchable movies, with John Witherspoon stealing scenes."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Nutty Professor",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "Shorthand for an entire stretch of his career playing four or five characters in one movie, a trick he's traced back to Peter Sellers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Shrek",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "The donkey that opened up a second, animated career and kept the checks coming for two decades."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dreamgirls",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "His only Oscar nomination: limited screen time, but 'when he is on, he's perfect.' He lost to Alan Arkin, and the panel still isn't over it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dolemite Is My Name",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The comeback: a Rudy Ray Moore biopic that led straight back to SNL and an Emmy. Included more for what it means to his career than for the film itself."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Thomas Vinterberg and Mads Mikkelsen on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Another Round",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Vinterberg had Mikkelsen in mind before there was even a story. The film wants to be about both the celebration and the damage of drinking. The cast went through a booze boot camp that calibrated exact blood-alcohol levels for each scene, and it closes on Mikkelsen's unscripted-feeling dance, which draws on his years as a professional dancer."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Hunt",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Their previous collaboration, and the reason they wanted to work together again."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hope",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Vinterberg's pick for the last great thing he'd seen."
        },
        {
          "title": "I'm No Longer Here",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Vinterberg's other pick, a Mexican film he called beautifully heartbreaking."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
